      "side": 1,
      "message": "I actually implemented this approach at http://review.skia.org/333278 but decided not to proceed with it and did this instead.\n\nChecking a type\u0027s complexity every time the IR Generator assembled an array type felt really bulky and needlessly heavyweight, and the practical difference between that implementation and this one was just a tighter limit. Having a tighter limit didn\u0027t actually add any value AFAICS--the only real goal is to prevent a stack overflow. (Also, by the time we\u0027ve reached the IR Generator, structs have mostly melted away into the symbol table, so the IR Generation stage couldn\u0027t actually report a struct\u0027s overage at the definition site; you had to do it when the type was used in the IR.)\n\nAlso, when I learned that WebGL enforces a struct nesting depth, that helped steer my decision to keep array depth and struct depth as separately enforced limits.",
